    "summary": "The Siege of Alesia (52 BC) was the decisive engagement of the [[event:1074|Gallic Wars]] and one of history's most remarkable engineering feats, in which Julius Caesar besieged the hilltop fortress of Alesia where the Gallic chieftain Vercingetorix had taken refuge, while simultaneously building a second ring of fortifications facing outward to defend against the massive Gallic relief army gathering to break the siege.\n\nCaesar's forces constructed approximately 11 miles of inner siege lines around Alesia (circumvallation) and 14 miles of outer defensive lines against the relief army (contravallation) — complete with towers, ditches, stakes, and obstacles — in a matter of weeks. The result was a force of roughly 60,000–80,000 Romans trapped between a fortified hill of 80,000 Gauls and a relief army reportedly numbering hundreds of thousands (ancient numbers likely exaggerated). When the relief army attacked the outer lines while Vercingetorix's forces attacked from within, Caesar moved reserves to threatened points, personally appearing where the danger was greatest. The coordinated attacks failed; the relief army dissolved and withdrew; Vercingetorix surrendered the following day.\n\nAlesia ended the organized Gallic resistance. Vercingetorix was held in Rome for six years, displayed in Caesar's triumph, and then strangled. The siege's engineering has been partially reconstructed by modern archaeology around the site of modern Alise-Sainte-Reine in Burgundy.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Alesia",
